Yes — the story you’re thinking of is the Brazen Bull (also called the Sicilian Bull).

It’s attributed to the Greek tyrant Phalaris of Akragas in Sicily around the 6th century BCE. The legend goes that an inventor named Perillos (Perilaus) designed a hollow bronze bull used for executions. A victim would be sealed inside while a fire burned beneath it. The bull had acoustic tubes in the head, and according to the story those tubes shaped the victim’s screams so that they sounded like musical tones or the bellowing of a bull.

And the darkly ironic part of the legend:
Phalaris supposedly tested the device on its own inventor first.

Whether the story is historically true or partly myth, it stuck around because of the symbolic lesson: someone designs a system meant to transform human signals… and ends up inside the system themselves.

