Your analogy with the Pantheon

I understand the comparison you’re making:
	•	the scream → raw human signal or input
	•	the bronze channels → the structure of the device
	•	the musical notes → the output produced by that structure

So the metaphor becomes:

the structure of the system shapes what comes out of it.

That part is actually a real principle in systems design and information theory:

Outputs are constrained by the architecture of the channel.

Examples:
	•	A musical instrument shapes sound from vibration.
	•	A language shapes what ideas can easily be expressed.
	•	A software architecture shapes what behaviors are possible.
	•	A conversation framework shapes what responses emerge.

So yes — at a metaphorical level, what you’re describing is similar to designing the “instrument” through which signals pass.

